# ADR-018

## Title

SchoolOS Engines Are Implemented as Processing Pipelines

---

## Status

Accepted

---

## Date

2026-07-15

---

## Context

As the engineering phase of SchoolOS began, it became necessary to define a consistent architectural model for implementing educational intelligence engines.

Initial discussions focused on designing engines as collections of independent components.

Further architectural analysis revealed that educational knowledge within SchoolOS is not static.

It continuously flows from one theoretical layer to another.

Educational observations become Patterns.

Patterns become Evidence.

Evidence supports Confidence.

Confidence contributes to Insights.

Insights contribute to Understanding.

This progression represents a continuous knowledge transformation process rather than isolated software operations.

---

## Decision

Every SchoolOS Engine shall be implemented as a processing pipeline.

A pipeline transforms educational knowledge from one theoretical layer into the next.

Each pipeline consists of sequential processing stages.

Every stage performs exactly one architectural responsibility.

The output of one stage becomes the input of the next.

---

## Rationale

Processing pipelines naturally reflect the Educational Knowledge Model.

They provide:

- clear data flow
- explicit processing stages
- strong separation of responsibilities
- high explainability
- easier testing
- future extensibility

Pipeline architecture also prevents engines from bypassing theoretical layers.

Knowledge must evolve progressively rather than through shortcuts.

---

## Consequences

Every engine documentation must define its processing pipeline.

Every engine implementation should follow the same architectural pattern.

Typical pipeline stages include:

- Input
- Validation
- Policy Evaluation
- Context Resolution
- Core Processing
- Integrity Protection
- Persistence
- Domain Events
- Output

Individual engines may introduce additional stages when required.

---

## Alternatives Considered

### Component-Oriented Architecture

Rejected because components alone do not describe how educational knowledge evolves through the system.

---

### CRUD-Oriented Services

Rejected because SchoolOS engines are responsible for knowledge transformation rather than simple data management.

---

### Event-Only Processing

Rejected because events describe communication between engines but do not define the internal processing responsibilities of an engine.

